    "faq": {
      "type": "brand-faq",
      "blocks": {
        "faq_1": {
          "type": "faq",
          "settings": {
            "question": "What is the difference between powder-actuated and gas-actuated fixing tools?",
            "answer": "<p><strong>Powder-actuated tools (PAT)</strong> use a blank cartridge to fire a pin into concrete or steel — they are powerful and suited to heavy-duty structural fixings. <strong>Gas-actuated tools</strong> like the Spit Pulsa use a gas fuel cell and battery ignition for lighter, faster operation — ideal for high-volume MEP fixings such as cable trays, conduit clips and pipe brackets.</p>"
          }
        },
        "faq_2": {
          "type": "faq",
          "settings": {
            "question": "What type of anchor should I use for concrete?",
            "answer": "<p>It depends on the load and substrate condition. For light to medium loads, <strong>Tapcon self-tapping concrete screws</strong> are the fastest option — no plugs required. For heavy structural loads, use <strong>mechanical expansion anchors</strong> or <strong>chemical resin anchors</strong>. For cracked concrete or seismic zones, specify <strong>ETA Option 1 approved</strong> anchors. Always check the design load tables.</p>"
          }
        },
        "faq_3": {
          "type": "faq",
          "settings": {
            "question": "What are fire-rated fixings and when do I need them?",
            "answer": "<p><strong>Fire-rated fixings</strong> are anchors and fasteners tested to maintain structural integrity during a fire for a specified period (typically 30, 60, 90 or 120 minutes). They are required wherever fixings penetrate or support <strong>fire compartmentation</strong> — fire barriers, fire-stopping around service penetrations, and structural connections in fire-rated zones. Spit's Tapcon HFL and anchor range includes fire-rated options.</p>"
          }
        },
        "faq_4": {
          "type": "faq",
          "settings": {
            "question": "What does ETA approval mean for construction fixings?",
            "answer": "<p><strong>ETA (European Technical Assessment)</strong> is an independently verified performance certificate for construction products. An ETA-approved anchor has been tested under controlled conditions for pullout resistance, shear capacity, cracked concrete performance and fire rating. It is required for structural and safety-critical fixings and allows engineers to specify with confidence.</p>"
          }
        },
        "faq_5": {
          "type": "faq",
          "settings": {
            "question": "Can I use the Spit Pulsa on steel as well as concrete?",
            "answer": "<p>Yes. The <strong>Spit Pulsa 800E</strong> is designed for fixing into both concrete and steel substrates. Use the correct pin type for each substrate — HC6 pins for concrete and steel-specific pins for metal decking and steel framing. Always check the maximum steel thickness in the technical data for your chosen pin.</p>"
          }
        },
        "faq_6": {
          "type": "faq",
          "settings": {
            "question": "Do you offer trade pricing on Spit products?",
            "answer": "<p>Yes. We offer <strong>competitive trade pricing</strong> across the full Spit range including Pulsa tools, Tapcon screws, anchors and consumables. Contact our trade team on <strong>01843 593 440</strong> or email <strong>sales@invictatools.co.uk</strong> for volume discounts and trade account enquiries. Free next-day delivery on all orders over £99.</p>"
          }
        }
      },
